citeinfo.title: Tax Code Areas for Adams County, Idaho for 2004 (.shp format)

descript.abstract: This data set reflects tax code area boundaries for Adams County as of January 1, 2004. This edition is available for levies and taxation in the calendar year 2004. It contains changes from January 1, 2003 to December 31, 2003.
descript.supplinf:
Each piece of property in Idaho lies in a "tax code area," which is defined by the combination of taxing districts that govern it. These taxing districts include counties, cities, schools, libraries, recreation districts, water, fire protection, ambulance, hospital, mosquito abatement, and others. Persons may live in different tax code areas if, for example, they are in different school districts or one home is in the city and the other in the county.
These data are intended to help:
- County assessors determine the property taxes on all privately owned parcels in the state.
- Utility companies (e.g. power, fuel pipelines, water and telecommunications) recalculate miles of line and other assets each year.
- The Tax Commission create reports for legislators.
descript.purpose: These data are intended for geographic display and analysis of Tax Code Areas for 2004. The data are intended to assist counties in disseminating tax levies and determining taxation on parcels of land. The data should be displayed and analyzed at scales appropriate for 1:500,000-scale data. No responsibility is assumed by the Idaho State Tax Commission or the State of Idaho in the use of these data.

procstep.procdesc: Determine if line was available in existing vector file in 1:24K or 1:100K from federal or state government (usually aliquot parts). If code area boundary did not follow an existing vector file, area was digitized from Tax Commission mylars. Current code areas are COGO'd in ARCINFO software in state plane NAD83 U.S. Survey foot. Polygons are built and cleaned then dissolved into large county database. Regions are then run on the database. County coverages merged into state plane zones in ArcView Geoprocessing Wizard. Output is shapefile. Each of the 3 state plane zones reprojected to IDTM. Merged IDTM zones to one statewide shapefile.
